# Factory Method Pattern — Transaction Types

## 1. Identified Problem

In the Bank Management System, [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124) objects are created in **four different controllers**, each for a different use-case:

| Controller | Transaction type(s) created | Lines of duplicated code |
|---|---|---|
| [DepositHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/DepositHandler.java#16-74) | `"Deposit"` | 8 setter calls |
| [WithdrawCashController](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/WithdrawCashController.java#17-94) | `"Withdrawal"` | 8 setter calls |
| [TransferHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/TransferHandler.java#20-112) | `"TransferDebit"`, `"TransferCredit"` | 2 × 8 setter calls |
| [MonthlyInterestHandler](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/controller/MonthlyInterestHandler.java#19-104) | `"InterestPosting"` | 8 setter calls |

Every creation site repeated the **same boilerplate pattern**:

```java
Transaction tx = new Transaction();
tx.setAccountNumber(...);
tx.setType("Deposit");          // ← hard-coded type string
tx.setAmount(...);
tx.setTimestamp(LocalDateTime.now());
tx.setPerformedBy(...);
tx.setNote(...);                // ← type-specific default
tx.setBalanceAfter(...);
tx.setReferenceCode("TXN-" + UUID.randomUUID()...);  // ← type-specific prefix
```

This created several concrete problems:

1. **Code duplication** — ~40 lines of nearly identical construction logic scattered across 4 classes.
2. **Hard-coded type strings** — the transaction type (`"Deposit"`, `"Withdrawal"`, etc.) was embedded as a raw string in each controller, risking typos and inconsistencies.
3. **Type-specific defaults buried in controllers** — each type has its own reference-code prefix (`TXN-`, `INT-`, `TRF-`) and default note text, but these details were mixed into business logic rather than centralised.
4. **Difficult to extend** — adding a new transaction type (e.g., `"Fee"`, `"Reversal"`) would require copying and adapting the same 8-line block yet again.

---

## 2. Why Factory Method Was Selected

The **Factory Method** pattern solves the identified problem by encapsulating object-creation logic in a dedicated creator class, so that the calling code is decoupled from the construction details.

### How it applies here

A new class, [TransactionFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#17-118), provides one **static factory method per transaction type**:

| Factory method | Encapsulates |
|---|---|
| [createDeposit(...)](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#23-39) | Type = `"Deposit"`, prefix = `TXN-`, default note |
| [createWithdrawal(...)](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#40-56) | Type = `"Withdrawal"`, prefix = `TXN-`, default note |
| [createTransferDebit(...)](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#57-74) | Type = `"TransferDebit"`, note = `"Transfer to …"` |
| [createTransferCredit(...)](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#75-92) | Type = `"TransferCredit"`, note = `"Transfer from …"` |
| [createInterestPosting(...)](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#93-109) | Type = `"InterestPosting"`, prefix = `INT-`, performer = `"System"` |

### How it solves each problem

| Problem | Solution |
|---|---|
| **Code duplication** | All 40 lines reduced to 5 one-liner calls. Construction logic exists in exactly one place. |
| **Hard-coded type strings** | Type strings are now defined once inside the factory, not in every controller. |
| **Scattered defaults** | Reference-code prefixes, default notes, and performer values are centralised in [TransactionFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#17-118). |
| **Difficult to extend** | Adding a new transaction type means adding one new factory method — no controller changes required. |

### Why not other patterns?

- **Abstract Factory** — would be appropriate if we needed *families* of related objects (e.g., all DAOs for a database backend). Here we are creating variants of a *single product* ([Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124)), which fits Factory Method better.
- **Builder** — would add complexity without benefit; the [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124) fields are fixed and every type needs all of them, so a fluent builder is unnecessary.

---

## 3. UML Class Diagram

```mermaid
classDiagram
    direction LR

    class Transaction {
        -int transactionId
        -String accountNumber
        -String type
        -BigDecimal amount
        -LocalDateTime timestamp
        -String performedBy
        -String note
        -BigDecimal balanceAfter
        -String referenceCode
        +getters/setters()
    }

    class TransactionFactory {
        -TransactionFactory()
        +createDeposit(accountNumber, amount, balanceAfter, performedBy, description)$ Transaction
        +createWithdrawal(accountNumber, amount, balanceAfter, performedBy, description)$ Transaction
        +createTransferDebit(sourceAccountNo, amount, balanceAfter, performedBy, destAccountNo, refCode)$ Transaction
        +createTransferCredit(destAccountNo, amount, balanceAfter, performedBy, sourceAccountNo, refCode)$ Transaction
        +createInterestPosting(accountNumber, interest, balanceAfter, monthlyRate)$ Transaction
        -generateReference(prefix)$ String
    }

    class DepositHandler {
        +postDeposit(accountNo, amount, description) int
    }

    class WithdrawCashController {
        +withdrawCash(accountNo, amount, description) int
    }

    class TransferHandler {
        +transferFunds(customerId, sourceAccountNo, destAccountNo, amount) String
    }

    class MonthlyInterestHandler {
        +postMonthlyInterest() int
    }

    TransactionFactory ..> Transaction : «creates»
    DepositHandler ..> TransactionFactory : «uses»
    WithdrawCashController ..> TransactionFactory : «uses»
    TransferHandler ..> TransactionFactory : «uses»
    MonthlyInterestHandler ..> TransactionFactory : «uses»
```

> **Reading the diagram:** The four controllers on the right **depend on** [TransactionFactory](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/TransactionFactory.java#17-118) (dashed arrows with `«uses»`). The factory in turn **creates** [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124) instances (dashed arrow with `«creates»`). Controllers no longer directly construct [Transaction](file:///c:/Users/Youssef/Documents/Uni/Software/Semester%201/Project/Implementation/JavaApplication6/src/main/java/com/bms/domain/entity/Transaction.java#10-124) objects — they delegate to the factory.
